metadata.name: Rough Cuts #67
metadata.description:
Abstract generative artwork that explores composition and form by cutting canvas with straight lines. Coded brushwork gives a real-painting look to each piece.

Options:

- press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to save hi-res PNG images

Created using p5js.

@VolatileMoods, July, 2022.

metadata.name: FIRESTARTER #14
metadata.description:
The trance-like effects of a bonfire, the chemical-colored flames in the laboratory or the simple comfort of a traditional hearth fire. 

Any combination of 16 color palettes and 3 borders are available, some more rare than others. 

Flame movement, size and shape are randomly generated.

To download a full resolution still image (2048 x 2048) double click/tap. 

@orlainberlin X @KRANKARTA

metadata.name: Ongemak #77
metadata.description:
Wabi-sabi (侘寂): appreciate impermanence and imperfection

There is little chance of a 'perfect' work of art. The small imperfections require reflection. 

The variation and randomness give the work some asymmetry, common in wabi-sabi esthetics. Because of a limited color palette and the simple shapes used, the works keep their simplicity (another principle of wabi-sabi). The noisy texture gives it some roughness, indeed again a core principle of wabi-sabi. 

The colors are reminiscent of the 70s and 80s. Some think that everything was better in the past. The trick is to enjoy the moment.

Thinking about impermanence is sometimes uncomfortable, 'ongemak' in Dutch, but also valuable.

metadata.name: The Modern Prometheus #48
metadata.description:
We are collections of the various people we've met. Each one of us is different but also is different to everyone we meet. We construct ourselves out of others' identities, traumas, shared experiences, and stories we tell ourselves (and have told about us). 

Like the resurrected monster, we live and learn through the way others react to us. We each yearn to be loved, and lash out against things trying to harm us. Without empathy, we're all the protagonists of our own story, and the monster is someone else's.

Like Dr. Victor Frankenstein, we experiment and bring life to things that we can't fully comprehend. We also cannot understand the full extent of the unintended consequences of our actions.

Whether NFTs will be a net positive or negative to society is far from decided, and, like these creatures you're minting, you may find beauty or horror when all is said and done.

metadata.name: fxhash x thi.ng project template #454
metadata.description:
THIS IS NOT AN ARTWORK (at least not intentional)!

This NFT acts as a donation/funding mechanism for a new project template Git repo, providing a compact, ready-to-go scaffolding for generative art projects aimed at the fx(hash) platform/marketplace.

https://github.com/thi-ng/fxhash-tpl

This template evolved over time and has served as basis for some of the author's own NFT projects (https://www.fxhash.xyz/u/toxi). The template is aimed at TypeScript (but can be easily adapted to plain JavaScript) and, at the time of writing, uses Vite as dev & build tool, ensuring an altogether great & speedy workflow with minimal fuzz.

(In the future, I'm aiming to provide an alternative version for more advanced hybrid projects using TypeScript, Zig (https://ziglang.org) and WebAssembly (https://webassembly.org/)...)

Framework agnostic

Even though several packages from the https://thi.ng/umbrella ecosystem are used to provide various essential overarching functionality, the template is organized in such a way that the main parts are completely framework-agnostic. You should be able to easily plug in your own toolkit of choice, however I cannot promise to provide support for this myself (though happy to accept PRs, also in terms of further docs, how-tos, guides etc.)

Example project

A tiny, fully documented throwaway example sketch is included, illustrating the following:

- Overall project structure & build commands
- FXhash related setup
- Static & dynamic configuration and state (re)initialization (via dependency graph)
- FXhash PRNG wrapper & utilities
- Canvas & SVG conversion/export/download
- 2D geometry creation, transformation & drawing
- Basic vector algebra example usage


Keyboard shortcuts

- space :  pause/play animation
- x : download canvas as PNG
- s : download SVG version

In case of doubt, it's this example project what is used here for minting. The funding, however, will be used for the further maintenance of both this project template and supporting my other open source work. 20% are also donated to the FXhash development team itself.

Thank you for your support! 🙏😍

metadata.name: Polar Grid #161
metadata.description:
Polar Grid is part of the fxhash live minting experience at Proof of People, London 2022.

This is a study of color, motion, and composition, and an homage to cinema as an artform. Colorful shapes overlap and pulse in a ever repeating dance. An abstracted movie experience. Each color palette in the series (except one) is inspired by a different film director (if you want a real challenge, see how many you can guess without looking at the feature names).

The palettes were extracted from movie stills or movie posters and fine tuned by hand. As often, I have to thank independent tool makers for their indirect help. My gratitude goes to David Aerne for FarbVélo and Fabrizio Bianchi for Coolors.

The code for Polar Grid is based on early iterations of what ultimately became my carat series. Both projects come from the same fascination for color as a system, even though I used a different approach here. You could call this a carat prequel.

The animation is done using a technique called polar noise. This makes it so the motion of all elements ends up repeating in the same amount of time. This is useful for generating motion that loops perfectly while still appearing organic. In this particular case, the animation repeats every π × 100 seconds.

A challenge in building any generative system is to find the right balance between coherence and variety. I designed the system with the large edition size in mind. During development I generated hundreds of iterations and tweaked my code to make sure that every iteration is truly unique and fits the overall aesthetic of the collection.

I truly hope you will enjoy your own little abstract movie.

— Raphaël de Courville


Released: July 6th 2022

Medium: p5.js, html canvas, css

Reference: sk220621


**About the artist**

Raphaël de Courville is a generative artist, streamer, and educator. His artistic work is an exploration of generative systems, patterns, interactivity, and time. Born in Paris, he lives and works in Berlin.


**Instructions**

- Click/Tap or press SPACEBAR to play and pause the animation

In Fullscreen mode (desktop only):
- Press UP or DOWN arrows to adjust image quality (Note: this can affect performance)
- Press F to hide/show the browser UI

metadata.name: a necessary reaction #12
metadata.description:
This piece has an interesting (to me) history. I originally started by trying to clone my IRL physical painting style in Midjourney. I got very close, then I had the idea to make a generative piece that could recreate the Midjourney recreation of my physical paintings. 

As is the nature of things, this result has departed quite a bit from my original intentions. You can scroll through the last two weeks of my Twitter feed to follow the entire process and see the original source. During the course of this writing process, crypto crashed, and the piece got darker and darker. 

There are certain combinations which will result on a matte black on matte black image (that I've taken to calling "carbon mode." A mint is in carbon mode when both palettes are 1, with a gesture on top. This is definitely the darkest mint I've done for FxHash, or even in general, and matches my mood as I watch my net worth drill to the core of the Earth. I am, however, an optimist, and I fully expect to look back on this month and laugh. Hopefully in the not-too-distant future.

metadata.name: Neon Shadow #2
metadata.description:
A collection of geometric abstractions with architectural imagination.

The friction between painted and unpainted surfaces is what gives spatial depth to this work and makes you wonder whether you are looking from outside or inside.

Generative artwork by KINTSUGI BOI (@kintsugi_boi)

metadata.name: an unrelated entity #86
metadata.description:
An experiment in maximal minimalism. The human brain's ability to deduce patterns and imagery given the the most basic input has always amazed me. Three circles and a handful of straight lines become a blazing sun and tall trees on a plain. 

I say "maximal" because this is far more code than I normally use; the "paper" alone is more code than my last three mints combined. The icons in the lower left are as follows: 

First icon: a binary representation of the transaction hash. 
Second icon: a meter denoting number of "trees"
Remaining icons: denote the boolean traits - sun, ring, and leaves.

Created in p5.js
